{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489787"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"746"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/746"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.12,0.05,0.36,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67779"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/746"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44261"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67779"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic five days after an elective thyroidectomy with a one-day history of mild bilateral pleuritic chest pain. She has no significant medical history and takes enoxaparin 40 mg daily for post-operative thromboprophylaxis. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. On auscultation, there is a friction rub on the right side with no other abnormalities. A computed tomography pulmonary angiogram confirms several small bilateral pulmonary emboli. Her renal function is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase enoxaparin to 80 mg twice daily","Commence alteplase infusion","Cease enoxaparin and commence warfarin","Cease enoxaparin and commence apixaban","Commence unfractionated heparin infusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with small pulmonary emboli following recent surgery, despite prophylactic anticoagulation. Given her haemodynamic stability and small clot burden, outpatient management with oral anticoagulation is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing enoxaparin and commencing apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Direct oral anticoagulants are now first-line for treatment of pulmonary embolism in stable patients. Apixaban is given at 10 mg twice daily for 7 days followed by 5 mg twice daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing enoxaparin to 80 mg twice daily\u003C/strong\u003E would provide therapeutic anticoagulation, but oral anticoagulation is preferred when available as it avoids the need for injections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing alteplase infusion\u003C/strong\u003E with thrombolysis is reserved for massive pulmonary embolism with haemodynamic compromise (systolic blood pressure \u003C90 mmHg or heart rate \u003E100/min), which this patient does not have.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing enoxaparin and commencing warfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is a valid option but requires regular INR monitoring and several days of bridging with therapeutic dose heparin until therapeutic. Direct oral anticoagulants are now preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing unfractionated heparin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would require hospital admission for monitoring and is unnecessary given the availability of oral options in this haemodynamically stable patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Stable patients with small pulmonary emboli can be managed as outpatients with direct oral anticoagulants.","Prophylactic doses of anticoagulation (e.g. enoxaparin 40mg daily) should be escalated to treatment doses when VTE occurs.","Thrombolysis is reserved for massive pulmonary embolism with haemodynamic instability."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Venous Thromboembolism: prophylaxis (Internet). 2020.","Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Venous Thromboembolism: treatment (Internet). 2020.","Doherty, S. (2017). Pulmonary Embolism: an update. Australian Family Physician, [online], volume 46, No. 11, pg. 816-820. available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/november/pulmonary-embolism/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"746"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:36:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:40:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"746"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","n